Class StructureUtility

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.gtnewhorizon.structurelib.structure.StructureUtility

  • public class StructureUtility
extends Object
    Fluent API for structure checking!

    (Just import static this class to have a nice fluent syntax while defining structure definitions)

      • ofBlocksTiered

        public static <T,TIER> IStructureElementCheckOnly<T> ofBlocksTiered(ITierConverter<TIER> tierExtractor,
                                                                    @Nullable
                                                                    TIER notSet,
                                                                    BiConsumer<T,TIER> setter,
                                                                    Function<T,TIER> getter)
        A more primitive variant of ofBlocksTiered(ITierConverter, List, Object, BiConsumer, Function) Main difference is this one is check only.

        Note that if tierExtractor returns a null, this block will be rejected immediately. This makes null a potent candidate for notSet.

        See Also:

      • ofBlocksTiered

        public static <T,TIER> IStructureElement<T> ofBlocksTiered(ITierConverter<TIER> tierExtractor,
                                                           @Nullable
                                                           List<org.apache.commons.lang3.tuple.Pair<Block,Integer>> allKnownTiers,
                                                           @Nullable
                                                           TIER notSet,
                                                           BiConsumer<T,TIER> setter,
                                                           Function<T,TIER> getter)
        Element representing a component with different tiers. Player can use more blueprint to get hints denoting more advanced components.

        Implementation wise, this allows a block only when we don't yet have a tier, or the block at that location has the same tier as we already have.

        There is yet no TileEntity counterpart of this utility. Feel free to submit a PR to add it.

        Example:

        Assume you have 16 tier, each map to one block's 16 different meta. You will usually want something like this 

         public class Tile extends TileEntity {
     private static final Block B = getTargetBlock();
     private static final IStructureDefinition<Tile> S = IStructureDefinition.<Tile>builder()
            // ... addShape, and other elements
            .addElement('c', ofBlocksTiered((b, m) -> b == B ? m : null,
                                            IntStream.range(0, 16).mapToObj(i -> Pair.of(B, i)).collect(Collectors.toList()),
                                            -1,
                                            (t, m) -> t.tier = m,
                                            t -> t.tier))
            .build();
     private int tier;

     public boolean check() {
         tier = -1;
         if (!S.check(...))
             return false;
         return isTierAcceptable(tier);
     }
 }
        Parameters:
        tierExtractor - a function to extract tier info from a block.
        allKnownTiers - All known tiers as of calling. Can be empty or null. No hint will be spawned if empty or null. Cannot have null elements. First element denotes the most primitive tier. Last element denotes the most advanced tier. If not all tiers are available at definition construction time, use lazy(Supplier) or its overloads to delay a bit.
        notSet - The value returned from getter when there were no tier info found in T yet. Can be null.
        getter - a function to retrieve the current tier from T
        setter - a function to set the current tier into T

      • ofBlockUnlocalizedName

        public static <T> IStructureElement<T> ofBlockUnlocalizedName(String modid,
                                                              String unlocalizedName,
                                                              int meta)
        Denote a block using unlocalized names. This can be useful to get around mod loading order issues.

        DUE TO HISTORICAL REASONS, THIS WAS CALLED ofBlockUnlocalizedName, BUT IT ACTUALLY USES REGISTRY NAME INSTEAD.

        While no immediate error will be thrown, client code should ensure said mod is loaded and said mod is present, otherwise bad things will happen later!

      • ofBlockUnlocalizedName

        public static <T> IStructureElement<T> ofBlockUnlocalizedName(String modid,
                                                              String registryName,
                                                              int meta,
                                                              boolean wildcard)
        Denote a block using unlocalized names. This can be useful to get around mod loading order issues.

        DUE TO HISTORICAL REASONS, THIS WAS CALLED ofBlockUnlocalizedName, BUT IT ACTUALLY USES REGISTRY NAME INSTEAD.

        While no immediate error will be thrown, client code should ensure said mod is loaded and said mod is present, otherwise the element will effectively become an error().

        Will place block or hint using the given meta if wildcard is true.

      • ofBlockUnlocalizedName

        public static <T> IStructureElement<T> ofBlockUnlocalizedName(String modid,
                                                              String unlocalizedName,
                                                              int meta,
                                                              IStructureElement<T> fallback)
        Similiar to the other overload, but allows client code to specify a fallback in case said block was not found later when the element got called.

        DUE TO HISTORICAL REASONS, THIS WAS CALLED ofBlockUnlocalizedName, BUT IT ACTUALLY USES REGISTRY NAME INSTEAD.

        This is slightly different to using the other overload and another element in a ofChain(IStructureElement[]). Here fallback will only ever be used if this fails, where ofChain would form an OR relationship even if the mod is loaded and the block exists in registry.

        This allows you to compose different IStructureElement to form a OR chain. As with any other OR operator, this one exhibits short-circuiting behavior, i.e. it will not call next structure element if previous one succeeded. (*)

        This allows you e.g. accept both a glass block using ofBlock(Block, int, Block, int) and a piece of air using isAir(). It will not attempt to capture any errors though, so next one will not be tried if previous one would crash.

        (*): For survival auto place, it will * REJECT, if all structure element REJECT * SKIP, if 1 or more structure element SKIP and the rest structure element (0 or more) REJECT * any other result, **immediately** upon any structure element returns these other results. This behavior is not 100% fixed and might change later on, but we will send the notice on a best effort basis.

        Take care while chaining, as it will try to call every structure element until it returns true. If none does it will finally return false.

        Take care while chaining, as it will try to call every structure element until it returns true. If none does it will finally return false.

      • lazy

        public static <T> IStructureElementDeferred<T> lazy(Supplier<IStructureElement<T>> to)
        Similar to defer, but caches the first returned element returned and won't call it again. Initialization is not thread safe. These both allow the structure element **constructor** to access properties only present on the context object (e.g. GT5 multiblock controller), e.g. hatch texture index to use. Use `lazy` if the data you access will remain constant across different context object.

      • defer

        public static <T> IStructureElementDeferred<T> defer(Supplier<IStructureElement<T>> to)
        This will defer the actual instantiation of structure element until the structure code is actually called. This will allow the structure element constructor to access properties only present on the context object (e.g. GT5 multiblock controller), e.g. hatch texture index to use. Use this if it might change for the same structure definition, e.g. if your structure might switch mode and change some parameter, while basically remain the same shape. Using this while lazy(Supplier) is enough will not break anything, but would incur unnecessary performance overhead.
